Here's an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP and HTML:

**search.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to database (example: MySQL)
$conn = mysqli_connect("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

if (!$conn) {
    die("Connection failed: " . mysqli_connect_error());
}

// Get search query from URL or form submission
$query = $_GET["q"] ?? "";

// Query the database for matching results
$sql = "SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$query%'";
$result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);

// Check if there are any results
if (mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
    // Display search results
    echo "<h2>Search Results:</h2>";
    while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
        echo "<p>" . $row["column_name"] . "</p>";
    }
} else {
    // Display no results message
    echo "<p>No results found.</p>";
}

// Close database connection
mysqli_close($conn);
?>
```
**index.html**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Search form -->
    <form action="search.php" method="get">
        <input type="text" name="q" placeholder="Search...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <!-- Display search results here -->
    <?php include 'search.php'; ?>
</body>
</html>
```
**style.css**
```css
/* Add some basic styling to the search form */
input[type="text"] {
    width: 100%;
    height: 40px;
    padding: 10px;
    font-size: 16px;
}

button[type="submit"] {
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: #fff;
    border: none;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    font-size: 16px;
    cursor: pointer;
}
```
**How it works**

1. The `search.php` file connects to a database (in this example, MySQL) and retrieves the search query from the URL or form submission.
2. It queries the database for matching results using the `LIKE` operator and displays them on the page.
3. If no results are found, it displays a "No results found" message.

**Note**: This is a basic example, and you should modify it to fit your specific needs. You may also want to consider adding pagination, filtering, or other features depending on your requirements.

Also, please keep in mind that this code uses the `mysqli` extension for database interactions. Make sure to replace the connection parameters with your own values.

**Security Considerations**

* Be aware of SQL injection attacks when using user-input data (e.g., `$query`) in your queries.
* Use prepared statements or parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection vulnerabilities.
* Validate and sanitize user input before storing it in your database.

